MUSA508_MidtermProject: Home Price Predictions in Miami, FL & Miami Beach, FL

Kristin Chang and Jenna Epstein

10/16/2020

Introduction

What is the purpose of this project?

The purpose of this project is to build a better predictive model of home prices for Miami and Miami Beach, Florida. Our process follows the hedonic price prediction method, where the sale price of each house is determined by both internal characteristics of the house, and external characteristics that take into account local context. We draw upon open data sources to determine the relevant external features to incorporate into our model. Ultimately we use ordinary least squares (OLS) regression to estimate goodness of fit for our model.

Why should we care about it?

Home price prediction is a common use case for cities, as they leverage data for a variety of purposes, from tax assessments to land use to zoning. In looking to build a better predictive model for home prices, it is imperative to look beyond internal features and incorporate local context that influence buyers’ decision making.

What makes this a difficult exercise?

There are a few aspects that make this exercise particularly difficult. For one, we take into account both the city of Miami and Miami Beach - two cities in the greater Miami metropolitan area. These two cities, while only apart by a 10 mile stretch of water, have different contexts. As of 2020, the City of Miami has over 490,000 residents, making it the second largest in Florida. The city boasts a vibrant and diverse cultural scene, with different ethnic groups represented through dining and cultural establishments. Miami Beach, on the other hand, is much smaller, with around 89,000 residents (US Census Bureau,2019). Continuing from its historic role as a seaside getaway for the wealthy, it is known for its position as a glitzy yet laid-back coastal escape. The city maintains a vibrant culinary scene for locals and tourists alike, and the coastline is dotted with high-rise residences fancy hotels. Given the different contexts between these municipalities, our model needs to incorporate factors beyond internal home features.

Another challenge involves the lack of open data standardization and availability across Miami and Miami Beach. Both cities sit within the county of Miami-Dade, but the county’s open data portal does not contain the same level of data across the various municipalities. The city of Miami also has an additional open data portal, and while some of the data sources may be useful for feature engineering, it is only available at the Miami city level, and thus cannot be used in our analysis of two areas.

What is your overall modeling strategy?

Our overall modeling strategy involves robust feature engineering to account for contextual differences that may influence sale price. We start with internal feature engineering, based on the data provided. New variables are created to separate out houses that have a pool. We then move on to bringing in additional data to engineer external features and associate them with the dataset of houses provided. We then fit multiple statistical models using different combinations of features in order to get a best fit for our dataset. Details about the robust data collection and wrangling for new features as well as details about our statistical methods are discussed more in the following sections.

Briefly summarize your results.

Through exploratory analysis and statistical modeling, we determine that crime, zoning, flood risk insurance zone, distance to the coast, neighborhood, and presence of a pool are key factors when predicting future home sales prices. Our final model is the neighborhood model that factors in spatial processes that cause clustering in sales price.

# Helper Functions
qBr <- function(df, variable, rnd) {
  if (missing(rnd)) {
    as.character(quantile(round(df[[variable]],0),
                          c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T))
  } else if (rnd == FALSE | rnd == F) {
    as.character(formatC(quantile(df[[variable]]), digits = 3),
                          c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T)
  }
}

q5 <- function(variable) {as.factor(ntile(variable, 5))}

## nn function
nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  measureFrom_Matrix <- as.matrix(measureFrom)
  measureTo_Matrix <- as.matrix(measureTo)
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
    output <-
      as.data.frame(nn) %>%
      rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
      gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
      arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
      group_by(thisPoint) %>%
      summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
      arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
      dplyr::select(-thisPoint) %>%
      pull()
  
  return(output)
}

Internal Features

Pool

We leverage the dataset to engineer a new internal feature: Pool. This involves extracting the string “Pool” from the XF1 column (the “Extra Features” column where pools were listed) and assigning each house as “Yes” (having a pool) or “No” (not having a pool). Given the heat in the Miami area, we figure that having a private pool is likely to influence the sale value of a house. We use this in our final model.

Zoning

We select zoning as a feature to incorporate in our models. Looking at the dataset, not all houses are situated within residential zoning areas (single family homes, multi-family homes, duplexes, townhouses, and estates). Given the effects that zoning can have on house prices and value fluctuations (especially for residential areas adjacent to industrial or commercial areas), we felt it was important to incorporate in our exploration. We use this in our final model.

Additional Internal Home Features

We incorporate the following internal home features into our model building process: Adjusted Square Feet, Living Square Feet, Lot Size

## Creating a new variable by extracting "Pool" from the XF1 column. Instances of pools only occur in the first XF column.
miamiHousesPts <-
  miamiHousesPts %>%
  mutate(Pool= ifelse(str_detect(miamiHouses$XF1, "Pool"), "Yes", "No"))

External Features

We now turn to engineering and including external features by bringing in available open data.

Distance to Coast (miles)

Given the desirability of living close to a beach - especially in such a hot city - we create a calculated feature for the proximity of each house relative to the coastline. After pulling in the coastline data from OSM, we use the dist2line function in the geosphere package to calculate the distance from each house to the nearest part of the coast. We then convert it from meters (the function’s default) to miles, and include it as a new variable column in the dataset. The map below symbologizes each house in the dataset by its distance to the coast, in miles.

# First, pull coastline data from OpenStreetMap in an xml format. Note that we are calculating this feature before reprojecting studentsDataPts back to ESRI projection. Has to be in Lat/Lon to work for distance calculation.
coastline<-opq(bbox = c(xmin.osm, ymin.osm, xmax.osm, ymax.osm)) %>% 
  add_osm_feature("natural", "coastline") %>%
  osmdata_xml('coastline.osm')

# Then, read it back into R and transform it into an sf. 
coastline.sf <- sf::st_read('coastline.osm', layer = 'lines') %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("Long", "Lat"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant")

# Add to main data and convert to miles
miamiHousesPts <-
  miamiHousesPts %>%  
  st_transform(st_crs(coastline.sf)) %>%
  mutate(distCoast=(geosphere::dist2Line(p=st_coordinates(miamiHousesPts), line=st_coordinates(coastline.sf)[,1:2])*0.00062137)[,1])

# distcoast - log
# to remove negatives, taking 5-
miamiHousesPts <- miamiHousesPts %>%
  dplyr::mutate(distCoast.log=5-log(distCoast))

Now that coastline distance is calculated and included as a feature, we reproject our main data.

miamiHouses.sf <-
  miamiHousesPts %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("Long", "Lat"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant") %>%
  st_transform('ESRI:102658')

FEMA Flood Insurance Rate Zones

Given the proximity of Miami and Miami Beach to the ocean and increasing prevalence of tropical storms inundating lower-lying areas of South Florida, we seek to include a feature to account for flood insurance zones. Through Miami-Dade County’s open data hub, we read in a geojson file containing polygons for all of the FEMA-designated flood insurance rate zones in the county. We then do a spatial join of the flood zone polygons and the main data set to associate each house with whatever zone in which it is situated. Here are the definitions of each flood insurance zone within our study area. For more information, please visit https://www.miamidade.gov/environment/flood-maps.asp).

Zone Definition
ZONE AE (moderate to high flooding risk) Corresponds to areas with flood depths greater than three feet. Mandatory flood insurance purchase requirements apply.
ZONE AH (moderate to high flooding risk) Corresponds to areas of shallow flooding with average depths between one and three feet. Mandatory flood insurance purchase requirements apply.
ZONE VE (high flooding risk) Corresponds to coastal areas that have additional hazards associated with storm waves. There is at least a one-in-four chance of flooding during a 30-year mortgage. Mandatory flood insurance requirements apply.
ZONE X (moderate to low flooding risk) corresponds to areas where the chance of being flooded is reduced but not completely removed. FLood insurance is recommended by not required.

The map below illustrates Miami and Miami Beach houses color-coded by zone.

Crime Incidents (Burglary and Assault, May - September 2020)

Incorporating crime as a feature in our analysis requires data wrangling. Unlike the other open data obtained through the county’s portal, Miami-Dade hosts their crime data through a third-party mapping site (https://www.crimemapping.com/map/fl/miami-dadecounty). The data is publicly available for several categories of incidents occurring over the previous six months (from the user’s date of access). While it allows users view block-level locations of incidents, share maps, and print the data in table format, it does not have the functionality for downloading the tables in a csv format. This requires us to scrape the data from the printable tables into a digital spreadsheet. We decide to use burglary and assault incidents, as they are the ones in the past full few months that appear without our study area. The data is available at the block level, but there are no further geographical attributes associated with it. We leverage the tidygeocoder R package to geocode the block-level data and obtain coordinates. Given the block-level data provided, the geocoder also returns block-level addresses instead of more granular addresses. We acknowledge the spatial bias involved in associating houses with data based on block-level proximity. However, given that this is the most granularity available, we use the nearest neighbor function to account for crime exposure within a given distance of each house.

In the series of scatterplots below, the data points hug the lines, especially in the lower left sections. This suggests there is some correlation between sale price and crime exposure. We will explore this further in our multivariate regressions.

# Bring in geocoded data and transform it to an sf

  st_transform('ESRI:102658')

Elevation

Data for distance to the coastline coupled data for flood zone identification leads us to explore including elevation as an external feature. Elevation data is available to the public as raster data. This requires us to perform some additional data wrangling to transform it into a usable format for exploration and analysis. This involves downloading the most recent 5-feet Digital Elevation Model (DEM) from the United States Geological Survey and reading it into R using the raster library. After projecting it to the correct coordinate reference system, we convert it to a spatial points dataframe using the rasterToPoints function. Given the large size of this file and the amount of time for R to process it, we write it to a csv and remove all of the hundreds of coordinate points that fall well outside of Miami-Dade county. We then read the csv file back in, transform it to a simple features object, ensure it is transformed to the same coordinate reference system as our main data, and spatial join each point to the nearest house in our dataset using the st_nearest_feature join predicate . Finally, we convert this new elevation variable to numeric in order to explore the relationship between nearest elevation value and home price. As with the previous two additional features, we decide to exclude this. Our numeric variable for distance to coast and our categorical variable for flood zone identification ultimately prove to be better combined predictors in our tests to account for what effects elevation levels may have on prices. This makes sense because a lot of houses in Miami Beach especially sit at low elevations, but are still highly priced because of the desirability of location. Those choosing to live right on the beach may not have an issue with paying more money for flood insurance living in a higher risk zone right next to the coast.

Results

Training Set Multivariate Regression

In the above analysis, we were able to view how each individual feature affected its past sales price. However, a combination of features are attributed to a single home affecting value in a different way depending on the quality of those features. For instance, a 4 bed 4 bath home with a pool may sell for a much higher price than a 4 bed 4 bath home without a pool. The unique interaction among our features and their combined influence on sales price is why we use statistical models to predict future sales prices.

Our first model mirrors the mechanics of the analysis used to select our engineered features. It simply observes sales price as a function of ActualSqFt, Pool, distCoast.log, and crime_nn2.

reg2 <- lm(SalePrice ~ ., data = st_drop_geometry(trainSet.sf) %>%

K-Fold Cross-Validation Test

The next model we try is a k-fold cross-validation test. In this test, we are able to address potential issues caused by our unique training dataset by running the test multiple times using different training datasets. Recall prior to our first model, we first split the data up into a group of known and unknown sales prices. Instead of splitting up the known sales price group, we will run this test on the entire group.

The test will partition the known sales price group into 100 equal sized subsets to train and predict on. Because all actual sales prices are known in this group, we can then compare predictions to calculate errors as we did before.

fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", 
                           number = 100,
                           # savePredictions differs from book
                           savePredictions = TRUE)
set.seed(825)

    parks_nn3 = nn_function(st_c(st_centroid(miamiTrain.sf)), st_c(st_centroid(parks.sf)), 3), 
    parks_nn4 = nn_function(st_c(st_centroid(miamiTrain.sf)), st_c(st_centroid(parks.sf)), 4),

Conducting a Moran’s I test on our errors will be able to tell us more about spatial clustering:

## A Moran's I that is higher than our 999 random permutations confirms there is spatial autocorrelation in our model errors. In other words, variation in SalePrice is related to a spatial process that is currently omitted from our model. 
moranTest <- moran.mc(validSet.sf$SalePrice.Error, 
                      spatialWeights.test, nsim = 999)

ggplot(as.data.frame(moranTest$res[c(1:999)]), aes(moranTest$res[c(1:999)])) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = moranTest$statistic), colour = "#FA7800",size=1) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(title="Observed and permuted Moran's I",
       subtitle= "Observed Moran's I in orange",
       x="Moran's I",
       y="Count",
       caption="validSet SalePrice.Error") +
  plotTheme()

The observed high Moran’s I indicates that the variance in sales price is related to a spatial process not accounted for in our model. Our next model will address this issue by incorporating a new neighborhood feature to account for clustering at the neighborhood level.

Neighborhood Model

Similar to our very first model, this last model observes sales price as a function of neighborhood name, crime_nn2, Zoning, FZONE, distCoast.log, Pool. We can run the model multiple times and review its results to decide which features to include by identifying the combination yielding the lowest error results.

left_join(
  st_drop_geometry(validSet.sf) %>%
    group_by(NAME) %>%

    group_by(NAME) %>%
    summarize(meanPrediction = mean(predict.fe)))

Discussion

Is this an effective model?

This is a somewhat effective model because we are able to predict across spatial variations in prices according to our neighborhood maps. The Moran’s I test results further confirm that spatial autocorrelation exists, drawing us to look at variable effects and variation at the neighborhood level.

According to your maps, could you account the spatial variation in prices?

As shown in the results, the neighborhood model’s map shows that spatial variation exists in prices, especially across the Miami and Miami Beach groups. Because the errors are consistent across neighborhoods, we feel that this is a more generalizable model than the cross-validation test.

Where did the model predict particularly well? Poorly?

The model predicted better in the city of Miami. This is likely due to the robustness of the open data that we used for Miami compared to Miami Beach. This is demonstrated through the crime variable: while the the crime mapping portal covers crime incidents across the county, incidents were reported in the city of Miami more frequently than for Miami Beach for the incident types and time period that we observed. In all of our tests, the crime nearest neighbor feature that we included showed statistical significance. It also improved the fit of the models - both cross-validation and neighborhood - when included.

The model was not as effective in predicting based on the distance to coast. In Miami Beach specifically, the variation in distance to coast is smaller compared to across the city of Miami, which makes this feature not as significant of a factor in house price prediction in Miami Beach. We hypothesize that there are other factors at play, such as the tourism industry and rental property presence in such a frequented vacation destination (Miami Beach) that are affecting home values.

What were some of the more interesting variables? Describe the more important features.

Some our our most interesting variables were external features engineered in our data exploration section. One of these variables was our wrangled crime data for burglary and assault incidents. Given the attention that the Miami area receives around high crime rate, we felt it would be an asset to include. We were expecting crime - in any of the nearest neighbor distance ranges - to be significant. We decided to use crime nearest neighbor two because it accounted for exposure at close proximity to homes, but not at the highest granularity due to the block-level standardization of the data points.

We also felt that variables related to the question of flood risk - such as living in a FEMA flood risk insurance zone and distance to the coastline - were important to include. We also looked at elevation by bringing in a raster dataset of the 2015 5-ft Digital Elevation Model; however, adding in elevation on top of the other predictors proved redundant and was not a good fit for the model. This may be in part to the transformation of raster-level data to approximate address-level locations; a point-level topographic elevation dataset would be a better data source to investigate (such a digital model is not available through open data portals).

Zoning turned out to be important internal variable to include in our model. The zoning variable we did not originally think to factor in; however, after looking the zoning maps of the cities, we realized there were probably spatial processes previously omitted from the model, similar to the neighborhood fixed effect.

How much of the variation in prices could you predict? Describe the error in your predictions?

Our neighborhood model is able to predict sales prices with a mean absolute error of approximately $300,000 using crime, zoning, flood risk insurance zone, distance to the coast, neighborhood, and pool features. Our prediction errors may be acceptable in a social science field; however, our mean absolute percentage error of ~37% would not be applied to the real world from a data science perspective.

Conclusion

We would recommend our neighborhood model to Zillow because it accounts for spatial processes - both neighborhood effects and property zoning - that drive clustering of house prices. It also takes into account additional features - both internal and external - that consider buyers’ preferences, which influence home values. Our model does well with generalizability, but it could improve with accuracy. Perhaps incorporating more features accounting for differences between Miami and Miami Beach could help alleviate variation between the two municipalities. This would require Zillow to work with the city to obtain more robust datasets on features like land use, while also obtaining incident data from more consistent crime reporting.
